<exercise>
<statement><p>
Friendly (?) bees fly towards your face from all directions. The  speed of each bee is inversely proportional to its distance from your face.  Find a vector field for the velocity of the swarm.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Set your face to be at the origin, <m>(0,0,0)</m>.
</p>

<p>If <m>A</m> is <q>inversely proportional</q> to <m>B</m>, then there exists a constant <m>\alpha</m> such that <m>AB=\alpha</m>. That way when <m>|B|</m> goes up, <m>|A|</m> goes down, and vice-versa.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
If your face is at the origin, then <m>\vv(x,y,z)=-\frac{\alpha}{{x^2+y^2+z^2}}(x,y,z)</m> for some positive constant <m>\alpha</m>.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Set your face to be at the origin of our coordinate system, <m>(0,0,0)</m>. A bee at position <m>(x,y,z)</m> is a distance of <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}</m> from your face, heading in the direction <m>(-x,-y,-z)</m>. So, the unit vector indicating the direction of travel of one bee is <m>\frac{-1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}}(x,y,z)</m>. Now all we need to find is the length of the velocity vector, i.e. the speed of the bee.
</p>

<p>The speed of the friendly bee is inversely proportional to <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}</m>, its distance from your face. (Bees that are closer to you are buzzing towards you more excitedly.) So, the speed is given by <m>\frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}}</m> for some constant <m>\alpha</m>.
</p>

<p>The bee velocity has the direction of the unit vector <m>\frac{-1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}}(x,y,z)</m> with length  <m>\frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}}</m> for some positive constant <m>\alpha</m>. That is,
<me>
\vv(x,y,z)=-\frac{\alpha}{{x^2+y^2+z^2}}(x,y,z)</me>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Sketch the vector field
<m>\vv(x,y)=(x^2,y)</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Start with the regions where <m>\vv(x,y)\cdot\hi</m> and <m>\vv(x,y)\cdot\hj</m> are positive and negative. As you move up/down/left/right, do the vectors get longer or shorter? More horizontal or more vertical?
</p></hint>

<answer>

<sidebyside width="82%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaxis{5}{5}
\foreach \x in {-3,...,3}{\foreach \y in {-4,...,4}{
\POWER{\x}{2}{\xtmp}
\DIVIDE{\xtmp}{10}{\xtmp}
\ADD{\y}{0}{\ytmp}
\DIVIDE{\ytmp}{10}{\ytmp}
\POWER{\xtmp}{2}{\xtest}
	\POWER{\ytmp}{2}{\ytest}
	\ADD{\xtest}{\ytest}{\test}
	\ifdim \test pt  \lt  0.01 pt
	\draw[red, thick](\x,\y) --(\x+\xtmp,\y+\ytmp);
	{}
	\else
\draw[- \gt , red, thick] (\x,\y) --(\x+\xtmp,\y+\ytmp);
	\fi
}}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside></answer>

<solution><p>
Beginning as in Example <xref ref="eg_Vortex"/>, we note
<me>\vv(x,y)\cdot\hi=x^2 \begin{cases}
 \gt 0 &amp; x \neq 0\\
=0 &amp; x=0
\end{cases}</me>
 and
<me>\vv(x,y)\cdot\hj=y \begin{cases}
 \gt 0 &amp; y  \gt  0\\
=0 &amp; y=0\\
 \lt 0 &amp; y \lt 0
\end{cases}.</me>
That leads to the following picture:
</p>
<sidebyside width="43%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaxis{2.5}{2.5}
\foreach \x in {-1,0,1}{\foreach \y in {-1,0,1}{
\POWER{\x}{2}{\xtmp}
\DIVIDE{\xtmp}{2}{\xtmp}
\ADD{\y}{0}{\ytmp}
\DIVIDE{\ytmp}{2}{\ytmp}
\ifdim\xtmp pt=0pt
\else
\draw[- \gt , blue, thick] (\x,\y) --(\x+\xtmp,\y);
\fi
\ifdim\ytmp pt=0 pt
\else
\draw[- \gt , red, thick] (\x,\y) --(\x,\ytmp+\y);
\fi
}}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside>

<p>
This gives us a general idea to start with. Refining, we notice that when <m>x^2 \gt |y|</m>, then the vector <m>\vv(x,y)</m> will be more horizontal than vertical. As we move away from the <m>y</m>-axis in a horizontal line, the difference between <m>x^2</m> and <m>|y|</m> grows, so the vectors get more and more horizontal. However, for a fixed value of <m>x</m>, vectors farther from the axis will be more vertical than vectors closer to it.
</p>
<sidebyside width="82%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaxis{5}{5}
\foreach \x in {-3,...,3}{\foreach \y in {-4,...,4}{
\POWER{\x}{2}{\xtmp}
\DIVIDE{\xtmp}{10}{\xtmp}
\ADD{\y}{0}{\ytmp}
\DIVIDE{\ytmp}{10}{\ytmp}
\POWER{\xtmp}{2}{\xtest}
	\POWER{\ytmp}{2}{\ytest}
	\ADD{\xtest}{\ytest}{\test}
	\ifdim \test pt  \lt  0.01 pt
	\draw[red, thick](\x,\y) --(\x+\xtmp,\y+\ytmp);
	{}
	\else
\draw[- \gt , red, thick] (\x,\y) --(\x+\xtmp,\y+\ytmp);
	\fi
}}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Sketch the <em>direction</em> field of
<m>\vv(x,y) = \left( \sqrt{x^2+y^2} , \sqrt{(x-1)^2+(y-1)^2}\right)</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
<m>\vv(x,y)\cdot \hi</m> is the distance from <m>(x,y)</m> to the origin, while <m>\vv(x,y)\cdot\hj</m> is the distance from <m>(x,y)</m> to the point <m>(1,1)</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer>

<sidebyside width="66%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaaxis{3}{5}{3}{5}
\foreach \x in {-1,-.5,0,.5,1,1.5,2}{\foreach \y in {-1,-.5,0,.5,1,1.5,2}{
\POWER{\x}{2}{\xsquared}
\POWER{\y}{2}{\ysquared}
\ADD{\xsquared}{\ysquared}{\tmp}
\SQUAREROOT{\tmp}{\xtmp}
\DIVIDE{\xtmp}{4}{\xtmp}
\SUBTRACT{\x}{1}{\xtmpa}
\POWER{\xtmpa}{2}{\xtmpb}
\SUBTRACT{\y}{1}{\ytmpa}
\POWER{\ytmpa}{2}{\ytmpb}
\ADD{\xtmpb}{\ytmpb}{\tmp}
\SQRT{\tmp}{\ytmp}
\DIVIDE{\ytmp}{4}{\ytmp}
\POWER{\xtmp}{2}{\xtest}
	\POWER{\ytmp}{2}{\ytest}
	\ADD{\xtest}{\ytest}{\test}
	\ifdim \test pt  \lt  0.01 pt
	{}
	\else
	\SQUAREROOT{\test}{\L}
	\DIVIDE{\xtmp}{\L}{\xdir}
	\DIVIDE{\ytmp}{\L}{\ydir}
	\DIVIDE{\xdir}{2}{\xdir}
	\DIVIDE{\ydir}{2}{\ydir}
\draw[- \gt , red, thick] (2*\x,2*\y) --(2*\x+\xdir,2*\y+\ydir);
	\fi

}}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside></answer>

<solution>

<p>Although ultimately we'll sketch only unit-length vectors, we can still find the direction of <m>\vv(x,y)</m> by finding its <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m> components.
</p>

<p>Note <m>\vv(x,y)\cdot \hi</m> is the distance from <m>(x,y)</m> to the origin, while <m>\vv(x,y)\cdot\hj</m> is the distance from <m>(x,y)</m> to the point <m>(1,1)</m>. Both these numbers are always nonnegative. This leads to the following sketch:
</p>

<sidebyside width="66%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaaxis{3}{5}{3}{5}
\foreach \x in {-1,-.5,0,.5,1,1.5,2}{\foreach \y in {-1,-.5,0,.5,1,1.5,2}{
\POWER{\x}{2}{\xsquared}
\POWER{\y}{2}{\ysquared}
\ADD{\xsquared}{\ysquared}{\tmp}
\SQUAREROOT{\tmp}{\xtmp}
\DIVIDE{\xtmp}{4}{\xtmp}

\ifdim\xtmp pt=0pt
\else
\draw[- \gt , blue, thick] (2*\x,2*\y) --(2*\x+\xtmp,2*\y);
\fi
\SUBTRACT{\x}{1}{\xtmpa}
\POWER{\xtmpa}{2}{\xtmpb}
\SUBTRACT{\y}{1}{\ytmpa}
\POWER{\ytmpa}{2}{\ytmpb}
\ADD{\xtmpb}{\ytmpb}{\tmp}
\SQRT{\tmp}{\ytmp}
\DIVIDE{\ytmp}{4}{\ytmp}

\ifdim\ytmp pt=0 pt
\else
\draw[- \gt , red, thick] (2*\x,2*\y) --(2*\x,\ytmp+2*\y);
\fi
}}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside>

<p>
When <m>(x,y)</m> is far from the origin, its distance from <m>(0,0)</m> is almost the same as its distance from <m>(1,0)</m>. So, we expect <m>\vv(x,y)</m> to be approximately a scalar multiple of <m>(1,1)</m>.
</p>

<p>At <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>v(0,0)\cdot \hi=0</m>, so our vector is horizontal; similarly, <m>v(1,1)\cdot\hj=0</m> so this vector is horizontal. Vectors very near to <m>(0,0)</m> are nearly horizontal, while vectors near to <m>(1,1)</m> are nearly vertical.
</p>

<sidebyside width="66%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaaxis{3}{5}{3}{5}
\foreach \x in {-1,-.5,0,.5,1,1.5,2}{\foreach \y in {-1,-.5,0,.5,1,1.5,2}{
\POWER{\x}{2}{\xsquared}
\POWER{\y}{2}{\ysquared}
\ADD{\xsquared}{\ysquared}{\tmp}
\SQUAREROOT{\tmp}{\xtmp}
\DIVIDE{\xtmp}{4}{\xtmp}

\SUBTRACT{\x}{1}{\xtmpa}
\POWER{\xtmpa}{2}{\xtmpb}
\SUBTRACT{\y}{1}{\ytmpa}
\POWER{\ytmpa}{2}{\ytmpb}
\ADD{\xtmpb}{\ytmpb}{\tmp}
\SQRT{\tmp}{\ytmp}
\DIVIDE{\ytmp}{4}{\ytmp}
	\POWER{\xtmp}{2}{\xtest}
	\POWER{\ytmp}{2}{\ytest}
	\ADD{\xtest}{\ytest}{\test}
	\ifdim \test pt  \lt  0.01 pt
	\draw[red, thick](2*\x,2*\y) --(2*\x+\xtmp,2*\y+\ytmp);
	{}
	\else
\draw[- \gt , red, thick] (2*\x,2*\y) --(2*\x+\xtmp,2*\y+\ytmp);
	\fi
}}

\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside>
<p>
For the direction field, we normalize our vectors to have unit length.
</p>

<sidebyside width="66%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaaxis{3}{5}{3}{5}
\foreach \x in {-1,-.5,0,.5,1,1.5,2}{\foreach \y in {-1,-.5,0,.5,1,1.5,2}{
\POWER{\x}{2}{\xsquared}
\POWER{\y}{2}{\ysquared}
\ADD{\xsquared}{\ysquared}{\tmp}
\SQUAREROOT{\tmp}{\xtmp}
\DIVIDE{\xtmp}{4}{\xtmp}
\SUBTRACT{\x}{1}{\xtmpa}
\POWER{\xtmpa}{2}{\xtmpb}
\SUBTRACT{\y}{1}{\ytmpa}
\POWER{\ytmpa}{2}{\ytmpb}
\ADD{\xtmpb}{\ytmpb}{\tmp}
\SQRT{\tmp}{\ytmp}
\DIVIDE{\ytmp}{4}{\ytmp}

	\POWER{\xtmp}{2}{\xtest}
	\POWER{\ytmp}{2}{\ytest}
	\ADD{\xtest}{\ytest}{\test}
	\ifdim \test pt  \lt  0.01 pt
	{}
	\else
	\SQUAREROOT{\test}{\L}
	\DIVIDE{\xtmp}{\L}{\xdir}
	\DIVIDE{\ytmp}{\L}{\ydir}
	\DIVIDE{\xdir}{2}{\xdir}
	\DIVIDE{\ydir}{2}{\ydir}
\draw[- \gt , red, thick] (2*\x,2*\y) --(2*\x+\xdir,2*\y+\ydir);
	\fi

}}

\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Sketch the <em>direction</em> field of
<m>\vv(x,y)=(x^2+xy,y^2-xy)</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Factor <m>x^2+xy=x(x+y)</m> and <m>y^2-xy=y(x-y)</m>.
Chop the plane up into eight regions using the two coordinate axes and the lines <m>y=x</m>, <m>y=-x</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer>

<sidebyside width="58%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaxis{3.5}{3.5}
\foreach \x in {-3,-2.5,...,3.1}{

\POWER{\x}{2}{\xsq}
\foreach \y in {-3,-2.5,...,3.1}{
	\POWER{\y}{2}{\ysq}
	\MULTIPLY{\x}{\y}{\xy}
	\ADD{\xsq}{\xy}{\vx}
	\SUBTRACT{\ysq}{\xy}{\vy}
\POWER{\vx}{2}{\vxsq}
	\POWER{\vy}{2}{\vysq}
	\ADD{\vxsq}{\vysq}{\L}
	\SQUAREROOT{\L}{\l}
	\MULTIPLY{\l}{2}{\l}
	\ifdim \l pt = 0 pt
		{}
		\else
		\DIVIDE{\vx}{\l}{\dx}
		\DIVIDE{\vy}{\l}{\dy}
		\draw[thick, red,- \gt ] (\x,\y)--(\x+\dx,\y+\dy);
	\fi
}}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside></answer>

<solution><p>
The sign of <m>\vv(x,y) \cdot \hi = x(x+y)</m> depends on the signs of <m>x</m> and <m>x+y</m>. When they have the same signs, <m>\vv(x,y)\cdot \hi</m> is positive, so <m>\vv(x,y)</m> points to the right; when they have different signs, <m>\vv(x,y)</m> points to the left.
</p><sidebyside width="59%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw (0,-3)--(0,3) node[above]{$y$};
\draw (-3,3)--(3,-3) node[right]{$y=-x$};

\fill[pattern color=gray, pattern=NE lines, hatch distance=5pt, hatch thickness=0.8pt] (-3,3)--(3,-3)|-cycle;

\fill[pattern color=gray, pattern=EW lines, hatch distance=5pt, hatch thickness=1.0pt] (0,-3) rectangle (3,3);
\draw[ultra thick, blue,- \gt ] (1,0)--(2,0);
\draw[ultra thick, blue,- \gt ] (-2,0)--(-1,0);
\draw[very thick, blue,- \gt ] (-.5,2)--(-1.5,2);
\draw[very thick, blue, \lt -] (.5,-2)--(1.5,-2);
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Similarly, the sign of <m>\vv(x,y) \cdot \hj = y(y-x)</m> depends on the signs of <m>y</m> and <m>y-x</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="56%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw (-3,0)--(3,0) node[right]{$x$};
\draw (-3,-3)--(3,3) node[right]{$y=x$};

\fill[pattern color=gray, pattern=NW lines, hatch distance=5pt, hatch thickness=1.0pt] (-3,-3)--(3,3)-|cycle;

\fill[pattern color=gray, pattern=NS lines, hatch distance=5pt, hatch thickness=1.0pt] (-3,0) rectangle (3,3);
\draw[ultra thick, red,- \gt ] (-1,1)--(-1,2);
\draw[ultra thick, red,- \gt ] (1,-2)--(1,-1);
\draw[very thick, red,- \gt ] (2,1.5)--(2,.5);
\draw[very thick, red,- \gt ] (-2,-.5)--(-2,-1.5);
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside>

<p>
All together:
</p>

<sidebyside width="59%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaxis{3}{3}
\draw[help lines] (-3,-3)--(3,3) node[right]{$y=x$};
\draw[help lines] (-3,3)--(3,-3) node[right]{$y=-x$};

\foreach \x in {0,...,7}{
	\draw (0,0)+(45*\x+22.5:2.75cm) node[shape=circle,fill, minimum size=1mm, draw, inner sep=0](v\x){};}
\color{blue}
\foreach \x in {7,0,1,3,4,5}
	{\draw(v\x) node[right]{\Large$\rightarrow$};}
\foreach \x in {2,6}
	{\draw(v\x) node[left]{\Large$\leftarrow$};}
\color{red}
\foreach \x in {1,2,3,5,6,7}
	{\draw(v\x) node[above]{\Large$\uparrow$};}
\foreach \x in {0,4}
	{\draw(v\x) node[below]{\Large$\downarrow$};}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside>
<p>
Refining, we notice that  as we move straight up or down, <m>|\vv(x,y)\cdot \hi|</m> has its minimum along the lines <m>y=-x</m> and <m>x=0</m>. So, the vectors become more strongly vertical as we approach <m>y=-x</m> and <m>x=0</m> from above or below.
</p>

<p>Similarly, <m>|\vv(x,y)\cdot \hj|</m> has its minima along the lines <m>y=x</m> and <m>y=0</m>, so the vectors become more strongly horizontal as we approach <m>y=x</m> horizontally.
</p>

<sidebyside width="58%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaxis{3.5}{3.5}
\foreach \x in {-3,-2.5,...,3.1}{

\POWER{\x}{2}{\xsq}
\foreach \y in {-3,-2.5,...,3.1}{
	\POWER{\y}{2}{\ysq}
	\MULTIPLY{\x}{\y}{\xy}
	\ADD{\xsq}{\xy}{\vx}
	\SUBTRACT{\ysq}{\xy}{\vy}

	\POWER{\vx}{2}{\vxsq}
	\POWER{\vy}{2}{\vysq}
	\ADD{\vxsq}{\vysq}{\L}
	\SQUAREROOT{\L}{\l}
	\MULTIPLY{\l}{2}{\l}
	\ifdim \l pt = 0 pt
		{}
		\else
		\DIVIDE{\vx}{\l}{\dx}
		\DIVIDE{\vy}{\l}{\dy}
		\draw[thick, red,- \gt ] (\x,\y)--(\x+\dx,\y+\dy);
	\fi
}}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Sketch the vector field <m>\displaystyle \vv(x,y)=\left[\frac{1/3}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}(x,y)+\frac{1/3}{\sqrt{(x-1)^2+y^2}}(x-1,y)\right]</m>.
</p>

</statement>

<hint><p>
What is the geometric interpretation of each summand?
</p></hint>

<answer>

<sidebyside width="82%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaxis{5}{5}
\draw (0,0) node[vertex]{};
\draw (1,0) node[vertex]{};

\foreach \x in {-4,-3.5,...,4}{
\foreach \y in {-4,-3.5,...,4}{

\SUBTRACT{\x}{1}{\xless}
	\POWER{\xless}{2}{\xlsq}
	\POWER{\x}{2}{\xsq}
	\POWER{\y}{2}{\ysq}
	\ADD{\xsq}{\ysq}{\xy}
	\ADD{\xlsq}{\ysq}{\xly}

		\MULTIPLY{\xy}{\xly}{\testdomain}
		\SUBTRACT{\x}{.5}{\xtesta}
		\ABSVALUE{\xtesta}{\xtestb}
		\TRUNCATE[0]{\xtestb}{\testzero}
		\ADD{\testdomain}{\testzero}{\test}
		\ifdim \test pt  \lt .1 pt
		{}
		\else
		\SQRT{\xy}{\dena}
		\SQRT{\xly}{\denb}
		\DIVIDE{1}{\dena}{\ca}
		\DIVIDE{1}{\denb}{\cb}
		\ADD{\ca}{\cb}{\ymost}
		\MULTIPLY{\ymost}{\y}{\yunscaled}
		\DIVIDE{\yunscaled}{3}{\yy}
		\MULTIPLY{\ca}{\x}{\xa}
		\MULTIPLY{\cb}{\xless}{\xb}
		\ADD{\xa}{\xb}{\xunscaled}
		\DIVIDE{\xunscaled}{3}{\xx}

	\draw[red, - \gt ] (\x,\y)--(\x+\xx,\y+\yy);
	\fi
}}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside></answer>

<solution>

<p>The field <m>\vv(x,y)</m> is the sum, scaled by 1/3, of the unit vector pointing away from the origin and the unit vector pointing away from <m>(1,0)</m>. This tells us about a few regions:
<ul>
<li> Along the <m>x</m> axis between <m>(0,0)</m> and <m>(1,0)</m>, the vectors away from these points are pointing in opposite directions (and have the same length), so they cancel each other out. That is, <m>v(x,0)=0</m> for all <m>x \in (0,1)</m>.
</li>
<li> <m>v(0,0)</m> and <m>v(1,0)</m> are not defined.
</li>
<li><p>
	Along the <m>x</m>-axis outside of <m>[0,1]</m>, the vector pointing away from the point <m>(0,0)</m> is the same as the  vector pointing away from the point <m>(1,0)</m>. So, <m>v(x,0)=(-2/3,0)</m> for <m>x \lt 0</m> and <m>v(x,0)=(2/3,0)</m> for <m>x \gt 1</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="82%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaxis{5}{2}
\draw (0,0) node[vertex]{};
\draw (1,0) node[vertex]{};
\foreach \x in {-4,...,-1}
{\SUBTRACT{\x}{.33}{\xx}
\draw[- \gt , thick, red] (\x,0)--(\xx,0);}
\foreach \x in {2,3,4}
{\ADD{\x}{.33}{\xx}
\draw[- \gt , thick, red] (\x,0)--(\xx,0);}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside>
</li>
<li><p>
 As the distance from <m>(x,y)</m> to the origin grows, the vector pointing away from <m>(0,0)</m> looks more and more like the vector pointing away from <m>(1,0)</m>. So, our vectors far away from the origin look like vectors of length about 2/3, pointing away from the origin.
</p>

<sidebyside width="82%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\YEaxis{5}{5}
\draw (0,0) node[vertex]{};
\draw (1,0) node[vertex]{};

\foreach \x in {-4,-3.5,...,4}{
\foreach \y in {-4,-3.5,...,4}{

	\SUBTRACT{\x}{1}{\xless}
	\POWER{\xless}{2}{\xlsq}
	\POWER{\x}{2}{\xsq}
	\POWER{\y}{2}{\ysq}
	\ADD{\xsq}{\ysq}{\xy}
	\ADD{\xlsq}{\ysq}{\xly}

		\MULTIPLY{\xy}{\xly}{\testdomain}
		\SUBTRACT{\x}{.5}{\xtesta}
		\ABSVALUE{\xtesta}{\xtestb}
		\TRUNCATE[0]{\xtestb}{\testzero}
		\ADD{\testdomain}{\testzero}{\test}
		\ifdim \test pt  \lt .1 pt
		{}
		\else
		\SQRT{\xy}{\dena}
		\SQRT{\xly}{\denb}
		\DIVIDE{1}{\dena}{\ca}
		\DIVIDE{1}{\denb}{\cb}
		\ADD{\ca}{\cb}{\ymost}
		\MULTIPLY{\ymost}{\y}{\yunscaled}
		\DIVIDE{\yunscaled}{3}{\yy}
		\MULTIPLY{\ca}{\x}{\xa}
		\MULTIPLY{\cb}{\xless}{\xb}
		\ADD{\xa}{\xb}{\xunscaled}
		\DIVIDE{\xunscaled}{3}{\xx}
		\draw[red, - \gt ] (\x,\y)--(\x+\xx,\y+\yy);
	\fi
}}
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside>
</li>
</ul>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

